---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { instruments } from '../data/instruments';
import { countries, seededCountrySlugs } from '../data/countries';

const total = instruments.length;
const needVerify = instruments.filter((i) => i.needs_verification);
const proposed = instruments.filter((i) => i.status === 'proposed');
---

<Base title="Methodology" description="How ChipSettle works: a deterministic decision engine over a verified, source-linked database — no AI-generated answers.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 py-10 space-y-10">
    <header>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-slate-900 tracking-tight">Methodology</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        ChipSettle is a structured filter and decision engine, not a chatbot. Every answer comes
        from a verified database entry with a legal basis, a source link, and a verification date —
        nothing is generated by a language model. Legal and fiscal information must be traceable to a
        source, not inferred.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">How the decision engine works</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        The engine is a pure function. It takes your company profile and passes every instrument
        through a sequence of hard filters, then assesses eligibility and ranks the survivors:
      </p>
      <ol class="text-sm text-slate-600 space-y-2 list-decimal pl-5">
        <li><strong>Status:</strong> only active, expiring, or proposed instruments are considered.</li>
        <li><strong>Country:</strong> instruments for your target countries, plus all EU-level instruments.</li>
        <li><strong>Headquarters:</strong> only instruments with a specific HQ restriction can hard-filter here; EU-establishment requirements downgrade eligibility rather than exclude, because the premise is that you establish an EU entity.</li>
        <li><strong>Business model, size, sector, goal:</strong> instruments whose eligibility explicitly excludes your profile are removed.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        Surviving instruments get an <strong>eligibility status</strong> — eligible, likely eligible,
        conditional, or not eligible — based on soft signals such as EU-establishment requirements,
        local-substance conditions, discretionary approval, proposed status, and the €750M Pillar Two
        threshold.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Relevance scoring</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Results are ranked by a transparent, additive score that weights:</p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-slate-600 space-y-1.5 list-disc pl-5">
        <li><strong>Rule-based over discretionary.</strong> A legal entitlement you can self-assess is worth more than a competitive call you might lose.</li>
        <li><strong>Active over proposed.</strong> Enacted instruments outrank legislative proposals.</li>
        <li><strong>Fiscal and practical impact</strong> for your selected goal — e.g. IP boxes rank higher when your goal is IP domiciliation; infrastructure access ranks higher for pilot-line goals.</li>
        <li><strong>Goal alignment</strong> — instruments whose core purpose matches your goal rank above those where it is secondary.</li>
        <li><strong>SME uplift</strong> where an instrument is materially more generous to SMEs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        Entries that document an <em>absence</em> (such as Germany's lack of an IP box) and entries
        with parameters still pending verification are deliberately ranked lower, but still shown, so
        comparisons stay honest.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Local presence: entity, branch, or none</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        A foreign company does not always need to form a new legal entity (GmbH/BV/SARL) to access an
        instrument. Each instrument now records one of three levels:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-slate-600 space-y-1.5 list-disc pl-5">
        <li><strong>No local presence required</strong> — the point does not depend on where you are established.</li>
        <li><strong>Local tax presence required</strong> — a branch office (a permanent establishment of your existing company) is sufficient. Most R&amp;D tax credits, payroll instruments, and IP boxes fall here, because they attach to domestic tax liability, not to a specific legal form.</li>
        <li><strong>Separate legal entity required</strong> — the applicant must be its own legal person. Most grant programs fall here, because the funding agreement is contracted with a legal entity.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        Every matched instrument shows this on its detail page, the action roadmap opens each country
        with a "Choose your entity path" recommendation based on what was actually matched, and the
        country page lists the branch and Employer-of-Record alternatives alongside full incorporation.
        This is orientation, not a substitute for corporate and tax advice — entity choice also affects
        liability, VAT, and banking, which this tool does not model.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Verification &amp; datedness</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        Every instrument carries a <strong>last-verified date</strong>, a verification source, and a
        next-review date. Entries verified more than six months ago show a warning. Entries with a
        recent change show a badge. This is deliberate: the tool is honest about its temporal limits
        rather than pretending policy is static.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm text-slate-600">
        <p class="font-medium text-slate-800 mb-1">Current database status</p>
        <ul class="space-y-1">
          <li>{total} instruments seeded; all verified as of 3 July 2026.</li>
          <li>{proposed.length} instrument marked <strong>proposed</strong> (EU Chips Act 2.0), flagged throughout the UI.</li>
          <li>{needVerify.length} instruments carry a "parameters pending verification" note where specific figures still need confirmation against the primary source.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Coverage notes</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        Instruments are currently seeded for {seededCountrySlugs.length} countries plus the EU level.
        The following target countries are selectable but do not yet have instruments in the database:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-sm text-slate-600 space-y-1 list-disc pl-5">
        {countries.filter((c) => c.slug !== 'eu' && !seededCountrySlugs.includes(c.slug)).map((c) => (
          <li>{c.flag_emoji} {c.name} — corporate tax context available; instruments planned.</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        The database is maintained through a CMS (Payload) so that non-technical editors can update
        parameters, add changelog entries, and refresh verification dates without code changes. There
        is no automated ingestion from external sources — every entry is manually verified against an
        official source.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">What this tool is not</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
        This is orientation, not advice. The engine tells you which instruments plausibly apply and
        where to read the law; it does not compute your tax position or guarantee eligibility. Consult
        a qualified tax, legal, or investment advisor before making decisions.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
